 ('47', '49', '4', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Federal Circuit Grants Privilege to Communications with non-Attorney Patent Agents\",\"slug\":\"federal-circuit-grants-privilege-to-communications-with-non-attorney-patent-agents\",\"postDate\":1458765551,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":[]}', '2016-03-23 20:39:12', '2016-03-23 20:39:12', 'ccbf2b00-5ff6-4941-bd31-e3d6922737d1'),
 ('48', '49', '4', '1', 'en_us', '2', '', '{\"typeId\":\"4\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Federal Circuit Grants Privilege to Communications with non-Attorney Patent Agents\",\"slug\":\"federal-circuit-grants-privilege-to-communications-with-non-attorney-patent-agents\",\"postDate\":1458765540,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"34\":\"\",\"33\":\"<p><i>In re Queen\\u2019s Univ. at Kingston<\\/i>, No. 2015-145 (Fed. Cir. Mar. 7, 2016), opinion available&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.cafc.uscourts.gov\\/sites\\/default\\/files\\/opinions-orders\\/15-145.Opinion.3-3-2016.1.PDF\\\">here<\\/a>.<\\/p><p>The Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, by writ of mandamus, reversed an order by the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Texas to compel production of documents containing communications between plaintiff Queen\\u2019s University and its non-attorney patent agents.<\\/p><p>The Federal Circuit held that communications \\u201crelating to \\u2018obtaining legal advice on patentability and legal services in preparing a patent application\\u2019 will be kept privileged,\\u201d even if such communications are between a client and a non-attorney patent agent. In doing so, the court relied upon the Supreme Court\\u2019s decision in<i>&nbsp;<\\/i><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/supreme.justia.com\\/cases\\/federal\\/us\\/373\\/379\\/case.html\\\"><i>Sperry v. State of Florida ex rel. Florida Bar<\\/i><\\/a>, 373 U.S. 379 (1963), hosted by justia.com, which had established that patent agents did practice law, albeit to a limited extent. The Circuit reasoned that protecting legal communications, even if neither party is an attorney, would serve Congress\\u2019 intent in establishing patent agents as an alternative to attorneys in this limited context. In so holding, the court established for the first time a patent-agent privilege, overcoming the general presumption against finding new forms of privilege.<br>This petition arose out of a patent infringement suit brought by Queen\\u2019s University against Samsung for alleged infringement of patented technologies that allow devices \\u201cto change their behavior based on the attentiveness of a user&mdash;for example, pausing or starting a video based on a user\\u2019s eye-contact with the device.\\u201d During discovery, Queen\\u2019s University withheld certain documents containing communications with patent agents. A magistrate judge granted a motion to compel production, which the District Court allowed over Queen\\u2019s University\\u2019s objections. Queen\\u2019s University then petitioned the Circuit for a writ of mandamus.<\\/p><p>In holding as it did, the court relied heavily on the&nbsp;<i>Sperry<\\/i>&nbsp;decision to establish that patent agents\\u2019 \\u201cpreparation and prosecution of patent applications\\u201d before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office does \\u201cconstitute[] the practice of law.\\u201d Congress has authorized patent agents to advise clients and consider the advisability of various forms of protection, though only within a limited scope of Patent Office proceedings. The court accordingly limited the scope of the newly-created patent-agent privilege to these particular areas of patent agents\\u2019 work, cautioning that \\u201cbefore asserting the patent-agent privilege, litigants must take care to distinguish communications that are within the scope of activities authorized by Congress from those that are not.\\u201d<\\/p><p>Judge Jimmie V. Renya dissented from the majority opinion, unconvinced that patent agents\\u2019 activities warranted a departure from the general \\u201cpresumption against the creation of new privileges.\\u201d Judge Renya emphasized that the factors that lead the Supreme Court to extend privilege to psychotherapist-patient communications in&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/supreme.justia.com\\/cases\\/federal\\/us\\/518\\/1\\/\\\"><i>Jaffee v. Redmond<\\/i><\\/a>, 518 U.S. 1 (1996), &nbsp;were not present here. The majority agreed that the factors cited in&nbsp;<i>Jaffee<\\/i>&nbsp;did not apply, but argued that those factors did not point&nbsp;<i>against<\\/i>&nbsp;an extension of privilege in this case. The dissent also questioned whether the legislature, rather than the court, ought to decide extensions of new privileges. In response to this, the majority pointed to 1934\\u2019s Rules Enabling Act, which allows the courts to craft the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure and of Evidence.<\\/p><p>The&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.natlawreview.com\\/article\\/re-queen-s-university-kingston-federal-circuit-recognizes-limited-patent-agent\\\">National Law Review<\\/a>&nbsp;provides a summary of the ruling. Practitioners from&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.lexology.com\\/library\\/detail.aspx?g=6782e46b-ce51-41ff-b04c-55c0317f6c2c\\\">Mayer Brown<\\/a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.lexology.com\\/library\\/detail.aspx?g=fbf25a95-a73f-47b0-bcc6-915bb43b5136\\\">Pearl Cohen<\\/a>&nbsp;have also weighed in, each highlighting the increased confidence that clients may have in communicating with their patent agents (a benefit the court had also noted). All three commentaries, however, urge caution with regard to the narrow categories of communications covered by the new patent-agent privilege. Pearl Cohen in particular speculated that new litigation might include disputes over whether communications fall within the privilege.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-03-23 20:48:42', '2016-03-23 20:48:42', '56dfe465-8a93-42f5-8a38-9e5efa85c099'),
