Jaffee v. Redmond<\\/em><\\/a>, 518 U.S. 1 (1996), &nbsp;were not present here. The majority agreed that the factors cited in&nbsp;<em>Jaffee<\\/em>&nbsp;did not apply, but argued that those factors did not point&nbsp;<em>against<\\/em>&nbsp;an extension of privilege in this case. The dissent also questioned whether the legislature, rather than the court, ought to decide extensions of new privileges. In response to this, the majority pointed to 1934\\u2019s Rules Enabling Act, which allows the courts to craft the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure and of Evidence.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.natlawreview.com\\/article\\/re-queen-s-university-kingston-federal-circuit-recognizes-limited-patent-agent\\\">National Law Review<\\/a>&nbsp;provides a summary of the ruling. Practitioners from&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.lexology.com\\/library\\/detail.aspx?g=6782e46b-ce51-41ff-b04c-55c0317f6c2c\\\">Mayer Brown<\\/a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.lexology.com\\/library\\/detail.aspx?g=fbf25a95-a73f-47b0-bcc6-915bb43b5136\\\">Pearl Cohen<\\/a>&nbsp;have also weighed in, each highlighting the increased confidence that clients may have in communicating with their patent agents (a benefit the court had also noted). All three commentaries, however, urge caution with regard to the narrow categories of communications covered by the new patent-agent privilege. Pearl Cohen in particular speculated that new litigation might include disputes over whether communications fall within the privilege.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-03-23 20:51:05', '2016-03-23 20:51:05', '578f08b7-b0c4-4e46-8148-7b534fdc0bc4'),
